rt","2018-06-28","Tourism: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department estimates the Welcome to Yorkshire brand has generated for the UK economy in (a) 2013, (b) 2014, (c) 2015, (d) 2016, (e) 2017 and (f) 2018 to date.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","158757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932279","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-03","<p>The Advisory Group that supports the independent Review of the Financial Reporting Council met for the first time on 25 May 2018. I understand the Group will meet approximately monthly until the end of the year.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-07-03T14:12:14.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932279/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932279/answer",,,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-28","Financial Reporting Council Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the first meeting of the advisory group of the independent review of the Financial Reporting Council will take place; and how often it will meet thereafter.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","158764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932280","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-03","<p>Sir John Kingman is conducting the review independently of my Department. I am therefore unable to speak for the review directly. However, I understand Sir John Kingman met the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) Stakeholder Advisory Panel on 26 June 2018, which included representatives from the Trades Union Congress (TUC).</p><p> </p><p>On 6 June 2018, the independent Review of the FRC published a public call for evidence, inviting views and information from those affected by the FRC’s functions and effectiveness. Sir John Kingman would welcome responses to the call for evidence from a wide range of stakeholders, including interested trade unions, before 6 August. The Review Secretariat can be contacted at <a href="mailto:FRCReview@BEIS.gov.uk" target="_blank">FRCReview@BEIS.gov.uk</a>.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-07-03T14:12:47.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932280/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932280/answer",,,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-28","Financial Reporting Council Independent Review: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether trade unions will be consulted as part of the independent review of the Financial Reporting Council.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","158765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932281","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-03","<p>Sir John Kingman asked not to receive a fee for his role undertaking the independent Review of the Financial Reporting Council. Members of the Review’s Advisory Group are also not remunerated for their involvement.</p><p> </p><p>The Review’s Secretariat is currently made up of 5.2 full time equivalent civil servants (receiving public sector pay) with the view that this will increase to 6.2 once a vacancy has been filled. The Secretariat also includes one secondee whose salary is met by Legal &amp; General. It is estimated that the costs of the Review will amount to approximately £210,000. This includes forecasted staff costs for the Secretariat, printing and travel and subsistence.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-07-03T14:11:51.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932281/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932281/answer",,,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-28","Financial Reporting Council Independent Review: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of the independent review of the Financial Reporting Council.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","158766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932282","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-05","<p>Small and medium-sized businesses that supply directly to supermarkets covered by the Groceries Supply Code of Practice are supported by the work of the Groceries Code Adjudicator, who ensures they are treated lawfully and fairly. The Government is also acting to tackle the late payment culture across all sectors. At Spring Statement 2018, my rt. hon. Friend Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer announced a call for evidence on how to eliminate unfair payment practices to small businesses, which will seek views on how the Government can go further to deliver a fair payment culture.</p><p> </p><p>More widely, small and medium-sized businesses in England can access support through GOV.UK and the Business Support Helpline and, through our Industrial Strategy, we will continue to back them to grow and create jobs by providing an environment in which they can thrive.</p><p> </p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-07-05T10:07:49.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932282/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932282/answer",,,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-28","Supermarkets: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support SME suppliers to supermarkets.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","158767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932283","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-05","<p>Direct suppliers to Sainsbury’s and Asda are already covered by the Groceries Supply Code of Practice and benefit from the work of the Groceries Code Adjudicator to ensure they are treated lawfully and fairly. They will continue to be protected by the Code and the Adjudicator should the proposed merger go ahead.</p><p>Under the Enterprise Act 2002 the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) have the powers to investigate, independently of Government, whether mergers raise competition issues that could have an impact on consumer choice. The Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has written to the Chief Executive of the CMA to express his view that, when assessing the proposed merger of Sainsbury’s and ASDA, the CMA should consider the possible impact on the supply chain.</p><p>The Government will continue to monitor closely this proposed merger.</p><p> </p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-07-05T10:05:46.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932283/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932283/answer",,,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-28","Asda: Sainsbury's","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he plans to take to support suppliers and consumer choice after the merger of Sainsbury’s and Asda.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","158768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932284","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-06","<p>A temporary release failure is recorded when alleged offending during ROTL is reported and there were 17 such failures in 2016, when there were 332,776 temporary releases and not 351,290 as indicated in the previous reply. In the 17 cases the charges fell into the following categories – five drugs, four violence against the person, two theft, two summary motoring, one sexual assault, one robbery, one miscellaneous and one other offence. Prison records do not routinely show the outcome of the charge, whether it was taken further by the police and, if so, whether there was a conviction, but do show that in each case the offender was transferred from open to closed prison conditions. Those convicted of an offence committed on ROTL are ineligible for further ROTL during the current sentence.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-07-06T10:37:39.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932284/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932284/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-28","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 28 June 2018 to Question 156397 on Prisoners' Release, which offence was committed in each of the 17 instances of re-offending; and what the consequences were for the prisoner in each case.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","158711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285","Ministry of Justice","true","2018-08-17","<p>The offence(s) for which each prisoner serving a sentence of less than 12 months was imprisoned, as at 31 March 2018, can be viewed in the table.</p><p> </p><p>Sentencing is a matter for our independent courts, who take into account all circumstances of the case, including any aggravating and mitigating factors.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst there is persuasive evidence that short custodial sentences of less than 12 months do not help some offenders turn their backs on crime, protecting the public will always be our top priority. Under this government, the most serious offenders are more likely to go to prison, and for longer, helping protect the public and keep communities safe.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-08-17T09:31:17.63Z","2018-12-11T13:36:42.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285/answer","PQ158712 Response Table (Revised 28 November).xlsx","PQ158712 Response Table (Revised 28 November).xlsx","Revised Table for PQ 158712","Revised Table for PQ 158712","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285/answer","Penrith and The Border ; Penrith and The Border","Penrith and The Border ; Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart ; Rory Stewart","Rory Stewart ; Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285/answer/previousversion/68131 ; http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285/answer/previousversion/72810","Biography information for Rory Stewart ; Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285/answer/previousversion/68131 ; http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285/answer/previousversion/72810","Biography information for Rory Stewart ; Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285/answer/previousversion/68131 ; http://data.parliament.uk/resources/932285/answer/previousversion/72810"