"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931887","Department for Transport","false","2018-07-06","<p>The High Speed Two Birmingham Interchange Station, near Birmingham Airport, is funded from the £55.7bn funding envelope (in 2015 prices). The estimate of the cost and funding arrangements are commercially sensitive.</p><p> </p><p>Last year the Chancellor announced £300m of funding for making passive provision on HS2 for junctions which would allow HS2 infrastructure to accommodate potential future Northern Powerhouse Rail and Midlands Connect services.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-07-06T11:14:54.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931887/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931887/answer",,,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-27","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Birmingham Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the cost of the High Speed Two station at Birmingham airport; and how that station will be funded.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","158261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931888","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-02","<p>This Government is committed to tackling fuel poverty. The <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fuel-poverty-statistics" target="_blank">latest statistics</a> on fuel poverty in England show the average fuel poverty gap – the amount needed on average to lift households out of fuel poverty – decreased to £326 in 2016, down from £341 in 2015.</p><p>The best long-term solution is to improve energy efficiency to bring the cost of heating homes down. That is why we have just consulted on focussing the whole of the £640m per year Energy Company Obligation on low income and vulnerable households from later this year.</p><p>We are also introducing a price cap to stop unreasonable price rises for those 11 million households on standard variable and default tariffs and under the Warm Home Discount Scheme, over 2 million low income and vulnerable households are provided with a £140 rebate off their energy bill each winter.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-07-02T16:25:52.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931888/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931888/answer",,,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-27","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the implication for his policies of 2.5 million people living in energy poverty.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","158267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931889","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-02","<p>The best long-term solution to fuel poverty is to improve energy efficiency to bring the cost of heating homes down. That is what we are doing through the Energy Company Obligation where we have consulted on focussing the whole of the scheme on low income and vulnerable households from later this year. We are also introducing a price cap to stop unreasonable price rises for those 11 million households on standard variable and default tariffs. Under the Warm Home Discount Scheme, over 2 million low income and vulnerable households are provided with a £140 rebate off their energy bill each winter.</p><p>Single parents and households in private rented accommodation will benefit from all of these measures. For those in the latter category, new Private Rental Sector Regulations came into force as planned on the 1st April 2018. They mean that all private landlords need to ensure that their properties reach at least a minimum Energy Performance Certificate rating of E before granting a tenancy to new or existing tenants. We also want to use new powers under the Digital Economy Act to help us focus support more accurately towards low income and vulnerable households living in fuel poverty.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-07-02T16:25:22.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931889/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931889/answer",,,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-27","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to support (a) single parents and (b) households in private rented accommodation at risk of energy poverty.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","158268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931890","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-05","<p>Fuel poverty figures by region can be found in Table 6 of the fuel poverty detailed tables: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fuel-poverty-detailed-tables-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fuel-poverty-detailed-tables-2018</a></p><p> </p><p>The number of households living in fuel poverty in Blackburn in 2016 is estimated to be 6,400 (15.4 per cent).</p><p> </p><p><em>Source: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/sub-regional-fuel-poverty-data-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/sub-regional-fuel-poverty-data-2018</a>, Table 5</em></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-07-05T10:13:16.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931890/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931890/answer",,,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-27","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of regional disparity in energy poverty; and what estimate his Department has made of the number of households living in energy poverty in Blackburn.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","158269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931891","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-02","<p>There has been a rise in the number of households in temporary accommodation for a variety of complex reasons. The number of households in temporary accommodation varies across the country as there are different issues in different areas, e.g. affordability pressure in London and the South East.</p><p>England has a strong homelessness safety net, providing protection to the most vulnerable in our society. Time spent in temporary accommodation means people are getting help and it ensures no child or family is without a roof over their head.</p><p>Successful homelessness prevention and relief has risen by 30 per cent between 2009/10 and 2016/17. However, the Government remains clear that one person without a home is one too many. We are committed to doing more to prevent people becoming homeless in the first place.</p><p>That’s why we have implemented the most ambitious legislative reform in decades, the Homelessness Reduction Act.</p><p>We have also committed £1.2 billion to tackle homelessness and rough sleeping including:</p><p>· £316 million of core funding for local authorities to prevent homelessness.</p><p>· £617 million in Flexible Homelessness Support Grant which local authorities can use strategically to prevent and tackle homelessness in their area;</p><p>· £72.7 million to support the implementation of the Homelessness Reduction Act;</p><p>· £20m Access to the Private Rented Sector Fund to increase access and sustainment of tenancies for those who are, or at risk of becoming homeless; and</p><p>· our £50 million to support 84 projects delivering an end-to-end approach to homelessness prevention.</p><p>MHCLG publishes regular statistics on temporary accommodation, rough sleeping, statutory homelessness and homelessness prevention and relief in England. These are published at a local authority level. The latest statistics can be found at: <a title="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics</a></p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","158265 ; 158266","2018-07-02T16:24:49.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931891/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931891/answer",,,,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-27","Temporary Accommodation: Blackburn","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of regional disparity in the number of households in temporary accommodation; and how many households are living in temporary accommodation in Blackburn.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","158270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931892","Cabinet Office","false","2018-07-05","<p>It is for individual Departments to ensure that written Parliamentary Questions (PQs) are answered in line with the Ministerial Code.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministerial Code sets out that Ministers must give accurate and truthful information to Parliament. The Cabinet Office produces guidance to officials on drafting answers to PQs. This is available on GOV.UK;</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/drafting-answers-to-parliamentary-questions-guidance.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-07-05T09:09:41.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931892/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931892/answer",,,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-06-27","Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons government departments do not substantively answer parliamentary questions on food bank usage.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","158271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931893","Department for Transport","false","2018-07-06","<p>This Government is determined to ensure that disabled people have the same access to transport as everyone else, and that they are able to travel easily and with confidence.</p><p> </p><p>Stations must display relevant information on information displays. In addition, through their Franchise Agreements train companies are required to make timetable information available and free of charge in booklets or similar format at staffed stations.</p><p> </p><p>Disabled People’s Protection Policies, required as a condition of a train operator’s licence, require train companies to demonstrate that the varied needs of different disabled passengers are taken into account when considering how information is communicated. All information about train services on display at stations must be made available through appropriate telephone help lines and staffed information points.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-07-06T11:11:24.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931893/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931893/answer",,,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-27","Railways: Visual Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that non-electronic copies of train timetables are available for people who have visual impairments or who cannot easily access timetables online.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","158165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931894","Home Office","false","2018-07-06","<p>I apologise for the delay in responding to the Hon. Members letter of 24 April 2018. A response will be sent shortly.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-07-06T10:52:07.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931894/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931894/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-27","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when his Department plans to respond to the letter of 24 April 2018 to the Minister of State for Immigration from the hon. Member for Slough on the case of a constituent, reference TD3808.","false","Biography information for Mr Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi","Slough","Mr Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi","158332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931895","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-06","<p>The Government has always been clear that we are committed to engaging the Crown Dependencies and Overseas Territories as we exit the EU, to ensure that their interests and priorities are properly taken into account.</p><p> </p><p>We are seeking a bold and ambitious economic partnership with the EU and want to have the greatest possible tariff- and barrier-free trade with our European neighbours, so that British companies, including Falkland Islands companies, have the maximum freedom to trade with and operate within European markets.</p><p> </p><p>I most recently met Hon. Teslyn Barkman, the Falkland Islands Legislative Assembly Member leading on Exit issues, at the 4th Joint Ministerial Council Overseas Territories (EU Negotiations) held on the 14th of June. Through discussions in this forum, supported by official level contact, the Government understands the importance to the economic wellbeing of the Falklands Islands of their access to the EU market for fish and meat.</p><p> </p><p>We also welcome the substantive input we have received from the Falkland Islands’ Government as the UK prepares to exit the EU.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-07-06T15:44:52.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931895/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931895/answer",,,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-06-27","UK Trade with EU: Falkland Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the Falkland Islands retains tariff free access to the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","158216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931896","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-02","<p>Pursuant to PQ 149587, stakeholders in Cumbria are developing their proposition to pilot the first Forestry Investment Zone. More detail will be available later in the year.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-07-02T14:59:48.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931896/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931896/answer",,,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-27","Forestry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress the Government is making on identifying Forestry Investment Zones as part of its Clean Growth Strategy.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","158152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931897","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-02","<p>Sir William Worsley was appointed by the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs as the national Tree Champion on 13 June:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/tree-champion-to-expand-englands-woodland" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/tree-champion-to-expand-englands-woodland</a>.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-07-02T13:17:34.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931897/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931897/answer",,,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-27","Forestry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether a short-list has been drawn up yet for the position of Tree Champion.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","158153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931898","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-02","<p>The Government’s Clean Growth Strategy, published in October 2017, responds to advice from the Committee on Climate Change and sets out how we will continue to decarbonise the UK to meet our climate mitigation obligations. The Strategy confirmed the important role of tree planting in contributing to carbon budget commitments, particularly in later carbon budget periods.</p><p> </p><p>The Committee on Climate Change emphasised the importance of tree planting in its independent assessment of the Strategy, published in January this year and in their annual progress report, published on 28 June 2018. We are developing a long-term trajectory for woodland planting to contribute to 5-year carbon budgets and deliver the 2060 aspiration to increase woodland cover in England to 12%.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-07-02T12:52:47.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931898/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931898/answer",,,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-27","Tree Planting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what advice he has sought from the Committee on Climate Change on tree-planting targets required to help meet UK climate change obligations.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","158154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931899","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-02","<p>​Issues pertaining to the Commission for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources are covered by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office's (FCO) Polar Regions Department, which currently has 6.5 full-time equivalent permanent staff. This team is also supported on the development of the Weddell Sea Marine Protection Area proposal by FCO Legal Advisers and scientific and technical experts from the British Antarctic Survey and the Centre for Environment, Fisheries and Aquaculture Science.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-07-02T16:02:10.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931899/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931899/answer",,,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-27","Antarctic: Marine Protected Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many full-time equivalent permanent staff in his Department are allocated to working on negotiations towards securing an agreement on the proposal to establish a Marine Protected Area in the Weddell Sea at the next annual meeting of the Commission on the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","158185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931900","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-07-02","<p>The information is not readily available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-07-02T16:45:42.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931900/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931900/answer",,,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-27","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average waiting time is for her Department to (a) process a revised decision notice and (b) amend a claim for universal credit in (i) the UK and (ii) Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","158224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931901","Department for Education","false","2018-07-05","<p>The revenue funding allocated for primary and secondary education for each financial year from 2009 to 2018 for Suffolk local authority is shown in the attached table. Funding is not allocated separately for primary and secondary pupils.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-07-05T15:20:48.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931901/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931901/answer","158213_Revenue_amounts_primary_and_secondary_education.pdf","158213_Revenue_amounts_primary_and_secondary_education.pdf","158213_Revenue_amounts_primary_and_secondary_educa","158213_Revenue_amounts_primary_and_secondary_educa","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931901/answer",,,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-27","Pupils: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much per pupil funding has been allocated to each (a) primary school and (b) secondary school in Suffolk in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","158213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931902","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-06","<p>NHS Digital publishes workforce statistics. The following table shows the full time equivalent (FTE) figures for mental health nurses working in National Health Service trusts and clinical commissioning groups in September each year since 2009 and latest data available.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>March 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mental Health Nurses, FTE (Total) of which:</p></td><td><p>46,155</p></td><td><p>45,384</p></td><td><p>43,691</p></td><td><p>42,446</p></td><td><p>41,432</p></td><td><p>40,357</p></td><td><p>39,247</p></td><td><p>38,930</p></td><td><p>38,695</p></td><td><p>39,358</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nurses – learning disabilities/ <br> difficulties</p></td><td><p>5,553</p></td><td><p>5,137</p></td><td><p>4,667</p></td><td><p>4,311</p></td><td><p>4,035</p></td><td><p>3,776</p></td><td><p>3,577</p></td><td><p>3,442</p></td><td><p>3,305</p></td><td><p>3,305</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nurses – psychiatry</p></td><td><p>40,602</p></td><td><p>40,247</p></td><td><p>39,024</p></td><td><p>38,135</p></td><td><p>37,397</p></td><td><p>36,581</p></td><td><p>35,671</p></td><td><p>35,488</p></td><td><p>35,390</p></td><td><p>36,053</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: NHS Digital Monthly Hospital and Community Health Services workforce statistics</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-07-06T12:37:30.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931902/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/931902/answer",,,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-27","Mental Health: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of